Welcome to the Nobody General

>Who is the Nobody?
The Nobody is a figure alive today who has extraordinary spiritual powers, including the ability to influence reality with his conscious and unconscious mind, and intuitively receive guidance from the forces of Heaven.
He works to elevate people to their true potential, opposing those who seek power over others. He's just like you, but he has found the kingdom of God within himself through sheer dedication, just like you will.

He isn't a savior; remember that it's you who creates your own reality. With your hands, thoughts, feelings, words, you are the creator of your story. No one can decide your fate except for you and God. Remember your right to power, to step up into your ultimate role as your highest self, should you choose to embark on that journey.

>What is the general picture?
It’s important we start replying more to the good posters and educating the hateful ones, so call upon their heads the forces of Heaven for peace, clarity, and wisdom. If this place is to be more than a squandered opportunity, an overgrown garden, it requires voices such as yours, but many more. This is a place for spiritual discussions and help, not drama, attention seeking, or social content; there are other boards for that.

Focus on increasing your service to all and be more loving to yourself and everyone in order to raise your vibrational and consciousness level, and learn to forgive yourself and others. This will change the vibration of the planet and raise our shared consciousness, making us a better humankind one person at a time.
None of us are perfect, it is by learning to admit and accept this fact one is able to learn, and grow in Truth. Heaven for all is real. Everyone's truest desires are mutual. The only motive is love.

If this is your first time here, just remember, it’s going to be ok, you may take shelter and find rest.

>Useful tips before posting:
•If you're a reader post that you're offering readings and what information is required from the querent; same goes for trading.
•Look for posts to determine if there's an active reader, what's needed and before posting, check if they finished reading already.
•Some readers will refuse to do certain readings - respect that choice. Do not harass readers if your query is refused/skipped.
•Traders should respect that a traded read will be granted, as per an agreement of trade. Free readers have the option of picking their queries.
•Bullshit queries will get bullshit answers. Same for vague queries.
•Making an AQ (air query) by not addressing a reader, in particular, is possible but doesn't guarantee an answer.
•Avoid making the same query repeatedly and/or to different readers in a short period of time, as this may lead to more confusion.
•Provide feedback when applicable and be considerate to the reader. We're a growing community, many readers are starting and need to know what they are doing right or wrong. Let's help each other to improve.

[{'no': 33573052, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)01:06:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>33573043
it's not.

The term was coined by the programmers at MIT's Project MAC. According to Fernando J. Corbató, who worked on Project MAC in 1963, his team was the first to use the term daemon, inspired by Maxwell's demon, an imaginary agent in physics and thermodynamics that helped to sort molecules, stating, "We fancifully began to use the word daemon to describe background processes that worked tirelessly to perform system chores".[2] Unix systems inherited this terminology. Maxwell's demon is consistent with Greek mythology's interpretation of a daemon as a supernatural being working in the background.

In the general sense, daemon is an older form of the word "demon", from the Greek δαίμων. In the Unix System Administration Handbook Evi Nemeth states the following about daemons:[3]

Many people equate the word "daemon" with the word "demon", implying some kind of satanic connection between UNIX and the underworld. This is an egregious misunderstanding. "Daemon" is actually a much older form of "demon"; daemons have no particular bias towards good or evil, but rather serve to help define a person's character or personality. The ancient Greeks' concept of a "personal daemon" was similar to the modern concept of a "guardian angel"—eudaemonia is the state of being helped or protected by a kindly spirit. As a rule, UNIX systems seem to be infested with both daemons and demons.

A further characterization of the mythological symbolism is that a daemon is something that is not visible yet is always present and working its will. In the Theages, attributed to Plato, Socrates describes his own personal daemon to be something like the modern concept of a moral conscience: "The favour of the gods has given me a marvelous gift, which has never left me since my childhood. Each week, you will be provided with another mystery. Consider this the church.


Here is this week's: (new one begins on Monday)

Jesus replied, “Is it not written in your Law: ‘I have said you are gods’? If he called them gods to whom the word of God came— and the Scripture cannot be broken— then what about the One whom the Father sanctified and sent into the world? How then can you accuse Me of blasphemy for stating that I am the Son of God?


There are some learned ones here, surely you see the riddle's answer.

The riddle is: Why did they believe he spoke blasphemy, and what is the logic behind Jesus' if-and-then question?

Today a frank clue is given again: If you add an apostrophe, the phrase in the Law is "I have said you are god's". In an actualized translation, this means "I have said you are mine", contextually translated "I have said you are my children". Jesus' question then is: If he called them His own children to whom the word of God came--and the Scripture cannot be broken-- then what about the child the Father set aside for the purpose of helping His children? How then can you accuse Me of insulting the Father for stating I am also the Child of God?

com:
One thing I think about all the time is the fact there are two totally opposite ways the world could work. Matter over mind, and mind over matter. All that you perceive of your "outer world" is perceived through your senses. You never get the actual thing itself. It's as if you have a big box totally impenetrable to sound, light etc. On the outside of the box are cameras, microphones etc.

These are connected by cables through the walls of the box to monitors, speakers etc on the inside of the box. You are sitting inside the box watching the monitors, listening to the speakers etc. You get the image and sound which is produced by the technology. You never get the actual thing which is outside the box. That's how humans work.

And the interesting thing is that you can never prove that what you get is what's actually outside, or that there is anything at all on the outside. That's the basis of the philosophical idea of solipsism. Close the curtains of your windows. You can't prove that there is a world outside your room, and that it doesn't get created the instant you open your door.

You can't prove that people you meet when you go outside would be there regardless of you, or whether they were put there specifically for you to encounter. I think this is the key to understanding religion. The outside world is not a fixed thing. It's fluid. It appears physical but it's in your mind only. Furthermore the past doesn't exist.

The past is memories in your mind only. And the future doesn't exist. It's an imagined outcome of events only. The past is no longer in existence, and the future doesn't exist yet. Only the present moment exists. Always. I think about this a lot. As I'm sitting alone in my room I can't prove that all of my enemies actually exist beyond my memories of them. And for all you know those memories might be implanted, like a dream.

https://youtu.be/0drT_L4G8w8

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solipsism

https://youtu.be/tLVA07_ISUk?t=37

Yes. Your senses are fallible precisely because they are dependent on an input. Even a thing that could think without any hypothetical input vectors - whether this thing is abstract, like a computer, or an imaginary machine, or physical, like a cell or a brain - it's comprehension is dependent on an input. In that sense, there is a point of failure, and thus, it is imperfect.
So even if you could prove something - the fact that you had to prove it means that it isn't true. The fact that there was ever a possibility that you had to prove it, means it isn't true.
If you follow this line of reasoning, you will realize something: anywhere where you are questioning, is a place that is incomplete. For a heaven to be real it would be without questions. It would be without even comprehension.
In this sense, this world might truly be completely material and 'realistic.' But you know, deep down, that it doesn't matter what the truth is: it's never true because of your own existence, which is predicated upon knowledge.
Thus there is another world: another world where everything already is, without critique, and thus without friction: that is the world all at once. This is what you identify within yourself that creates the gulf of comprehensibility between "you" and then the world of comprehension. In the world of comprehension, peace is nothingness, as nothingness is the only place without comprehension. But this is wrong.
The real place is that you are *already and always there.* You are already nothing.
Your soul is the yolk and the world is the egg. But we only see the shell. For all we know, the egg is empty: people see the egg and say "the egg must have a yolk inside, because it is an egg." My egg is empty, and nobody can tell me it is or isn't. They only see the shell.
Reality is a tug of war between a conception where there is 'something and nothing,' and another, where there is something, nothing, and then perpendicularly to those two; everything.', 'time': 1670654487, 'resto': 33572188}, {'no': 33573291, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)01:50:17', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>33572553

There's a lot of math that went into the Great Pyramid and the location at which it was built and how it was aligned. Google it and look at the various pages that go into how the Golden Ratio and Pi and Euler's number and the Fine Structure Constant are all built into it. Pyramid can be broken down into two words: pyr and mid, fire in the middle. The idea that pyramid got its name from the Greek word "pyramis", a wheat cake, is a deliberate misdirection in my opinion and I can believe the wheat cake got its name from the Pyramid rather than the other way around.

So what was its purpose? I believe it was used to create another universe. Hear me out.

So imagine planets are birthed from stars, grow old and die just like people. In the lifespan of our solar system we might have 1000 worlds birthed, grow old and die just like Earth. The whole of human history from beginning to end takes place on these worlds. Each world has a mission of creating another Great Pyramid and another universe below it. Time in that smaller universe will move more rapidly. It will see 1000 worlds, each tasked with creating another Great Pyramid and universe and so on, down the infinite multiverse we go. So using sacred geometry and the laws of nature, the gods (or God) creates a procession of universes chasing an infinitely smaller point.

The End of the age is timed to coincide with the birth of a new planet and the death of the old planet (Earth, in our case). When this occurs the Great Pyramid with the multiverse will be powered down and the universe directly below it will come to an end. The universe at the infinitely smallest point will be escaping faster than the wake of destruction from above can reach it, so all is well and this string of universes will go on forever.

Hi, /x/. I will preface this saying I am not a Christian, but my recent deep dive into Kabbalah has made me start to consider the possibility of an occult interpretation of Christianity.
Jehovah seems to be very much bound by rules. In 2 Kings, the king of Moab sacrifices his son in order to win a battle, and it works, the Israelites, God's own chosen, have to back down because the blood magick was that potent. The Carthaginians would sacrifice the highest born, most beautiful, often firstborn boys in times of extreme trouble (which is why I don't agree with the pro-life comparison of abortion to child sacrifice since it's usually the lowest type of people who get them done), and although I know Crowley was trolling, his description of a highly intelligent young boy being the most ideal human sacrifice got my noggin-jogging.
>What's a king to a god?
If a beautiful royal is the ideal human sacrifice, what about God, not a God, but the supreme god, in the form of a young royal, being offered as a sacrifice? There is a quote somewhere, I can't find it, I saved it but it's from Eliphas Levi calling the Catholic mass an extremely powerful occult ritual.
I used to be a Mormon, and still collect some far out deep-lore Mormon literature. The concept of humans becoming gods, gaining in power, through the blood-sacrifice of God. If Christian saints are half the time just pagan gods in a new skin, doesn't that mean Christians (or at least the Catholics and Orthodox) believe human beings can become gods after death (or at least mini-gods, for now) by living by correct principles? Thanks to God's blood being sacrificed?
I read about Wandering Bishops yesterday, and that Aleister Crowley himself was possibly one:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Episcopus_vagans
If you had a Wandering Bishop to transfigurate the wine into the blood of God, could you do blood magick rituals without the need to actually provide living, organic blood?

com: does math work the same in other realities?
last_replies:
[{'no': 33573030, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)01:02:12', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>33572980
Math doesn't "work" in this reality. It is impossible to square the circle.', 'filename': '8c71dd00442e8c783223c78bf1309107', 'ext': '.png', 'w': 814, 'h': 748, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 114, 'tim': 1670652132085683, 'time': 1670652132, 'md5': 'HFloA8y6ZNxs3D7si82nLw==', 'fsize': 75244, 'resto': 33572980}, {'no': 33573189, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)01:34:29', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'Math depends on the reality of the temporal = 0. But we live in a reality of temporal > 0. On paper and in process math works but in reality everything's in flux so math doesn't even work the same in our dimension.', 'time': 1670654069, 'resto': 33572980}, {'no': 33573316, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)01:53:33', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>33572980
In any situation it's absolutely impossible to ever prove that a mathematical statement is "the correct" one.
I mean, statements can be useful in specific scenarios... But there is no 1 statement that's THE statement.

Take something simple like 1+1=2. What situation in reality could you say that absolutely applies to?
Perhaps if I have 1 rock and I bring another one close by. But how close does it have to be? Or what if it adds up to 3 instead of 2 (rock1, rock2, rock1&2) who's to say?
And it's easy to see that almost any physics equation can be missing terms. Terms could be so small that they're almost 0 in most cases, but you never know if they could become large in a fringe case and totally break your theory tomorrow.

>does math work the same in other realities?
>IN other realities?
I would say the answer is that math isn't IN any reality at all. It is it's own reality.
Thought itself is a collection of mental experiences.
So if you have a reality that has no thought, then there is no math. If you pull thought into that reality then along comes math. But it's still its own separate thing, like I wrote above it doesn't definitively map onto anything else in that reality. Although you can create an approximate map if you want (which is what we do).

Or a really simplified way to put it is that math is like a language. It's never equal to the thing it's trying to describe, since it's only symbolic references to it.', 'time': 1670655213, 'resto': 33572980}]
